  "answer": "Surah Al-Baqarah 2:3 establishes that believing in the \"unseen\" is a fundamental characteristic of the righteous [1]. This belief in the unseen anchors the theological framework for understanding realities like angels, Paradise, and Hellfire.\n\n**Belief in Angels and the Last Day**\nThe Quran explicitly mandates belief in these unseen concepts. Surah Al-Baqarah 2:177 defines true righteousness as believing in God, the Last Day, the angels, the Book, and the prophets [2]. Furthermore, Surah An-Nisa 4:136 warns that anyone who disbelieves in God, His angels, His books, His messengers, and the Last Day has strayed far from the truth [3].\n\n**The Realities of Hellfire and its Angelic Guardians**\nThe scriptures vividly describe the unseen realities of the Hereafter. Surah At-Tahrim 66:6 commands believers to protect themselves and their families from a Fire fueled by people and stones, which is guarded by severe and harsh angels who perfectly execute God's commands [4]. Surah Al-Muddathir 74:31 further establishes that the keepers of the Fire are exclusively angels, and their specific number was made a trial for disbelievers [5].\n\n**Paradise and Hellfire as Eternal Destinations**\nThe theological certainty of the Hereafter is anchored by verses defining the ultimate outcomes for humanity. Surah Al-Baqarah 2:81-82 contrasts the two eternal destinations, stating that those encompassed by their sins will be the companions of the Fire, while those who believe and do righteous deeds will abide eternally as companions of Paradise [6].",
